entry.description: An optically active form of lactic acid having (R)-configuration.
A trimethylxanthine in which the three methyl groups are located at positions 1, 3, and 7. A purine alkaloid that occurs naturally in tea and coffee.
An alpha-amino acid that consists of propionic acid bearing an amino substituent at position 2.
A ketohexose that is an isomer of glucose.
An anthocyanin cation consisting of delphinidin having a beta-D-glucosyl residue attached at the 3-hydroxy position.
Carbohydrates that are absorbed in the small intestine and provide carbohydrate for metabolism in monogastric animals.

A compound in which monosaccharide units are joined by glycosidic linkages. The term is commonly used to refer to a defined structure as opposed to a polymer of unspecified length or a homologous mixture. When the linkages are of other types the compounds are regarded as oligosaccharide analogues.
A tetrasaccharide consisting of sucrose having an alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->6)-alpha-D-galactosyl moiety attached at the 6-position of the glucose.

A polydisperse highly branched polysaccharide derivative composed of chains of D-glucopyranose residues in alpha(1->4) glycosidic linkage. The chains are joined together by alpha(1->6) glycosidic linkages. A small number of alpha(1->3) glycosidic linkages and some 6-phosphate ester groups also may occur. The branches in amylopectin typically contain 24 to 30 glucose residues.
Dietary fibre which does not dissolve in water and is inert to digestive enzymes in the upper gastrointestinal tract of monogastric animals.
A (1->4)-beta-D-glucan (cellulose) in amorphous form with a structure consisting of several hundred to over ten thousand D-glucose residues joined by beta(1->4) glycosidic linkages.
Polysaccharides composed of fructose residues.

Any mixture of complex, colloidal, macromolecular plant galacturonans containing a large proportion of D-galactopyranosyluronic acid residues in alpha-(1->4) linkage, the carboxy groups of which may be esterified to varying degrees by methyl groups or be partially or completely converted into salts. The structure shown is that of the parent polygalacturonan.
A mineral nutrient that represents a major proportion of the minerals required in the diet
Dietary supplement
A trihydroxyflavanone having a structure of naringenin prenylated at C-6.
A dihydroxyflavone in which the two hydroxy substituents are located at positions 4 and 7.

Any flavonoid that is a salt containing flavylium ion or 2-phenylchromenylium skeleton and its substituted derivatives together with an appropriate counterion. Aglycons of anthocyanins, they form a part of the large group of planr pigments.
An anthocyanin cation that is cyanidin(1+) carrying a single beta-D-galactosyl substituent at position 3.
An organic chloride salt of any anthocyanin.
A memeber of the class of anthocyanin chlorides that has cyanidin 3-O-beta-D-galactoside as the cationic counterpart.
A chalcone that is (E)-chalcone bearing four additional hydroxy substituents at positions 2 , 3, 4 and 4 .
A ketone that is 1,3-diphenylpropenone (benzylideneacetophenone), ArCH=CH(=O)Ar, and its derivatives formed by substitution.
An aryl beta-D-glucoside that is 3-hydroxyphloretin in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 2 is replaced by a 6-O-beta-D-xylosyl-beta-D-glucosyl group.
A member of the class of flavans in which one or more ring hydrogens are replaced by hydroxy groups.
A catechin with (2R,3R)-configuration.
Members of the class of hydroxyflavan that have a flavan-3-ol skeleton and its substituted derivatives.
A trihydroxyflavanone having a structure of naringenin prenylated at C-6.
The simplest member of the class of flavanones that consists of flavan bearing an oxo substituent at position 4.
A dihydroxyflavone in which the two hydroxy substituents are located at positions 4 and 7.

A flavonoid oligomer that is obtained by the oxidative coupling of at least two units of aryl-substituted benzopyran rings or its substituted derivatives, resulting in the two ring systems being joined together by a single or bond.

A heteroglycan consisting of beta-(1->4)-linked D-glucose (G) and D-mannose (M) in a proportion of 5:8. The basic polymeric repeating unit has the pattern: GGMMGMMMMMGGM, with branching through beta-(1->3)- and beta-(1->6)-glucosyl linkages. Acetate groups are present on C-6 every 9-19 units of the main chain.
A hydroxycinnamic acid that is cinnamic acid in which the phenyl ring is substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 4. It exists in cis and trans forms; the latter is the more common.
A monohydroxycinnamic acid in which the hydroxy substituent is located at C-3 of the phenyl ring.
A monohydroxycinnamic acid that is prop-2-enoic acid substituted by a hydroxyphenyl group at position 3.
A member of the class of coumestans that is 6H-[1]benzofuro[3,2-c]chromene substituted by an oxo group at position 6.
A glycosyloxyisoflavone that is daidzein attached to a beta-D-glucopyranosyl residue at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage. It is used in the treatment of alcohol dependency (antidipsotropic).
A glycosyloxyisoflavone that is glycitin carrying an acetyl substituent at position 6 on the glucose moiety.
A member of the class of 7-hydroxyisoflavones that is 7-hydroxyisoflavone substituted by an additional hydroxy group at position 4 .

A member of the class of pterocarpans that is the 3-O-methyl ether of (+)-6a-hydroxymaackiain (the 6aR,12aR stereoisomer). A phytoalexin found in pods of garden peas (Pisum sativum) and other plants of the pea family, including Tephrosia candida.
Any aliphatic monocarboxylic acid derived from or contained in esterified form in an animal or vegetable fat, oil or wax.
A tetradecenoic acid in which the double bond is at the 9-10 position and has Z configuration. Myristoleic acid has been isolated from Serenoa repens and has cytotoxic and apoptosis-inducing effects.
A family of polyunsaturated fatty acids that have in common a final carbon-carbon double bond in the omega-3 position, i.e., the third bond from the methyl end of the fatty acid.

An acylglycerophosphocholine resulting from partial hydrolysis of a phosphatidylcholine, which removes one of the fatty acyl groups. The structure is depicted in the image where R1 = acyl, R2 = H or where R1 = H, R2 = acyl.
An 3beta-sterol that is (22E)-ergosta-5,22-diene substituted by a hydroxy group at position 3beta. It is a phytosterol found in marine algae, fish, and rapeseed oil.
A tetradecenoic acid in which the double bond is at the 9-10 position and has Z configuration. Myristoleic acid has been isolated from Serenoa repens and has cytotoxic and apoptosis-inducing effects.

A hydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone that is 1,4-naphthoquinone in which the hydrogen at position 5 has been replaced by a hydroxy group. A plant-derived 1,4-naphthoquinone with confirmed antibacterial and antitumor activities.
Any napthoquinone in which the oxo groups of the quinone moiety are at the 1 and 2 positions of the naphthalene ring.
Dietary supplement
Dietary supplement
Dietary supplement
An icosatrienoic acid having three cis double bonds at positions 8, 11 and 14.
Dietary supplement
A 2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is propanoic acid in which one of the alpha-hydrogens is replaced by a hydroxy group.
A monosaccharide derivative that is hydroquinone attached to a beta-D-glucopyranosyl residue at position 4 via a glycosidic linkage.
A methyl ketone that is acetone in which one of the methyl groups has been replaced by a phenyl group.
Members of the class of phenols that contain 2 or more benzene rings each of which is substituted by at least one hydroxy group.
A gallate ester obtained by the formal condensation of gallic acid with the (3R)-hydroxy group of (-)-epigallocatechin.
Any of a group of astringent polyphenolic vegetable principles or compounds, chiefly complex glucosides of catechol and pyrogallol.
A proanthocyanidin isolated from Cinnamomum cassia.

Any phenylpropanoid derived from phenylalanine via dimerization of substituted cinnamic alcohols, known as monolignols, to a dibenzylbutane skeleton. Note that while individual members of the class have names ending ...lignane, ...lignene, ...lignadiene, etc., the class names lignan, neolignan, etc., do not end with an e.

Any phenylpropanoid derived from phenylalanine via dimerization of substituted cinnamic alcohols, known as monolignols, to a dibenzylbutane skeleton. Note that while individual members of the class have names ending ...lignane, ...lignene, ...lignadiene, etc., the class names lignan, neolignan, etc., do not end with an e.
A choline that is the parent compound of the cholines class, consisting of ethanolamine having three methyl substituents attached to the amino function.
A protein that accumulates in developing seeds or grains.
Dietary supplement
A carotenoid having the structure of beta-carotene but with a cis double bond at the 9,10-position.

Provitamin A is a name for β-carotene,[1] which has only about 1/6 the biological activity of retinol (vitamin A); the body uses an enzyme to convert β-carotene to retinol. In other contexts, both β-carotene and retinol are simply considered to be different forms (vitamers) of vitamin A.
Provitamin D2 is ergosterol
Provitamin B5 is a name for panthenol, which may be converted in the body to vitamin B5 (pantothenic acid).
Provitamin D2 is ergosterol
provitamin D3 is 7-dehydrocholesterol
Menadione is a synthetic provitamin of vitamin K.
A straight-chain, C22, long-chain saturated fatty acid.

A C18 straight-chain saturated fatty acid component of many animal and vegetable lipids. As well as in the diet, it is used in hardening soaps, softening plastics and in making cosmetics, candles and plastics.
A member of the class of 7-hydroxyisoflavones that is 7-hydroxyisoflavone substituted by an additional hydroxy group at position 4 .
Member of the class of isoflavones bearing at least one hydroxy group.

Any terpenoid derived from a diterpene. The term includes compounds in which the C20 skeleton of the parent diterpene has been rearranged or modified by the removal of one or more skeletals (generally methyl groups).

A biochemical role played by any micronutrient that is an organic compound. Vitamins are present in foods in small amounts and are essential to normal metabolism and biochemical functions, usually as coenzymes. The term vitamines (from vita + amines) was coined in 1912 by Casimir Funk, who believed that these compounds were amines.
A fat-soluble vitamin required for the synthesis of prothrombin and certain other blood coagulation factors.
A subclass of carotenoids consisting of the oxygenated carotenes.
An acyclic psi,psi-carotene having cis double bonds at C-7, -7 , -9 and -9 .
A group of fat-soluble retinoids produced via metabolism of provitamin A carotenoids. Vitamin A is involved in immune function, vision, reproduction, and cellular communication.
Vitamin A function, included in growth and development, maintenance of the immune system, and good vision.
Compounds that destroy thiamine in food, which occur naturally in food or are produced in food as a result of microbial or other action.
An agent that prevents the excretion of cholin in urine, a water-soluble nutrient grouped within the B-complex vitamins.
Vitamin B12, also known as cobalamin, is a water-soluble vitamin involved in metabolism
Provitamin D2 is ergosterol
Provitamin B5 is a name for panthenol, which may be converted in the body to vitamin B5 (pantothenic acid).

Vitamin B6 is one of the B vitamins, and thus an essential nutrient. Its active form, pyridoxal 5′-phosphate, serves as a coenzyme in some 100 enzyme reactions in amino acid, glucose, and lipid metabolism.
The L-enantiomer of ascorbic acid and conjugate acid of L-ascorbate.
water soluble vitamin

Vitamin D is a group of fat-soluble prohormones, which can be obtained from sun exposure, food and supplements. Vitamin D is biologically inactive and converted into the biologically active calcitriol via double hydroxylation in the body.

fat soluble vitamin. A chromanol that is chroman-6-ol which is substituted at position 2 by a methyl group and (also at position 2) either a saturated or a triply-unsaturated hydrocarbon chain consisting of three isoprenoid units.
A fat-soluble vitamin required for the synthesis of prothrombin and certain other blood coagulation factors.
A carotenol, the structure of which is (6 R)-beta,epsilon-carotene hydroxy-substituted at C-3 with R-stereochemistry.

A member of the class of arabinoxylans that consists of a polymer chain of beta-(1->4)-linked D-xylopyranose units, many of which are 2- or 3-substituted, or 2,3-disubstituted by alpha-L-arabinofuranosyl residues.
